Date: September 24, 2024
Objective: Detailed Design Development
Record:

Main Ideas from Project Proposal:
Highlighted the necessity of precise subsystem integration to ensure seamless operation and user control, focusing on the interplay between mechanical movements and electronic controls.

Studied additional resources on H-bridge motor control and servo motor torque optimization to enhance design accuracy.
Reviewed Bluetooth communication protocols to ensure reliable data transmission between subsystems.
Diagrams and Schematics:

Enhanced the Block Diagram to include detailed connections and signal flows between all subsystems, highlighting the interaction between the Car System and Remote System.
Design Problems and Decisions:

Signal Integrity: Addressed potential signal interference by implementing shielding and proper grounding techniques in the PCB layout.
Power Supply Stability: Decided to incorporate capacitors near voltage regulators to smooth out voltage fluctuations and reduce noise.
Equations and Formulas:

PWM Signal Calculation:
Determined the appropriate PWM frequency to balance motor control precision and signal stability.
PWM Frequency=1𝑘𝐻𝑧
PWM Frequency=1kHz
Chose 1kHz as it provides a good balance between control resolution and minimal noise interference.
Documentation of Testing and Debugging Process:

Began drafting subsystem requirements, focusing on the Car System and Remote System components, ensuring all specifications are met.
Conducted preliminary tests on servo motor responsiveness using PWM signals generated by the ESP32.
Important Notes for Debugging:

Ensure that all PWM signals are free from jitter to maintain precise motor control.
Validate that the voltage regulators maintain stable outputs under dynamic load conditions.
Analysis and Proposed Solutions for Debugging Problems:

Identified potential issues with PWM signal distortion and planned to use filtering techniques to clean the signals.
Proposed implementing watchdog timers to reset the system in case of communication failures.

Scheduled signal integrity tests using an oscilloscope to visualize PWM signals and identify any distortions or anomalies.
Documentation of Final Performance Tests and Design Verification:

Planned to conduct comprehensive tests of the Control Subsystem during the Design Review to ensure reliable operation.
